\begin_layout Section
How to Calculate Genomic Inflation Factor and λgc for GWAS
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
You have conducted your genome-wide association study (GWAS) and have tested
 each genetic variant for an association with your trait of interest.
 Now it is time to investigate if there are any systematic biases that may
 be present in your association results.
 A common way to do this is to calculate the genomic inflation factor, also
 known as lambda gc (λgc).
 By definition, λgc is defined as the median of the resulting chi-squared
 test statistics divided by the expected median of the chi-squared distribution.
 The median of a chi-squared distribution with one degree of freedom is
 0.4549364.
 A λgc value can be calculated from z-scores, chi-square statistics, or
 p-values, depending on the output you have from the association analysis.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Follow these simple steps to calculate lambda GC using R programming language.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
